Task 1 - Text-Analyzing a simple set of documents.

We collect reviews data for IMBD movie (top 250 movie) - Schindlers List. We collect both the positive reviews (50) and negative reviews (50) along with the user rating given to the review. URL- http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0108052/reviews?filter=love;filter=love;start=0.

Reviews data collection from IMDB website for movie Schindlers List.

We observe that for positive reviews the ratings given by the users is 10/10 and for negative reviews the rating given by users is mostly 1/10. Few users have given the ratings 2/10 for negative reviews. We create the ratings vector for the reviews using these values.

library("rvest")

counts = c(0,10,20,30,40)
reviews = NULL
ratings = NULL
for (j in counts){
  url1 = paste0("http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0108052/reviews?filter=love;filter=love;start=",j)
  url2 = paste0("http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0108052/reviews?filter=hate;filter=hate;start=",j)
  
  page1 = read_html(url1)
  page2 = read_html(url2)
  
  reviews1 = html_text(html_nodes(page1,'#tn15content div + p'))
  ratings1 = rep(10,length(reviews1))
  if (reviews1 != 'NULL') ratings1 = rep(10,length(reviews1))
  reviews2 = html_text(html_nodes(page2,'#tn15content div + p'))
  #ratings2 = rep(1,length(reviews2))
  if (j < 35) {
  ratings2 = rep(1,length(reviews2))  
  }  
  if (j == 40) {
  l = length(reviews2)
  ratings2[1:(l-2)] = 1
  ratings2[(l-1):(l)] = 2
  }
  
  reviews.positive = setdiff(reviews1, c("*** This review may contain spoilers ***","Add another review"))
  reviews.negative = setdiff(reviews2, c("*** This review may contain spoilers ***","Add another review"))
  
  reviews = c(reviews,reviews.positive,reviews.negative)
  ratings = c(ratings,ratings1,ratings2)
  
}

reviews = gsub("\n",' ',reviews)
writeLines(reviews,'C:/Vaibhav/ao/ta/asgnat/schindlersreviews.txt')
rev_rat = data.frame(reviews, ratings)
write.table(rev_rat,'C:/Vaibhav/ao/ta/asgnat/schindlersrevrat.txt',row.names = FALSE)

text.clean = function(x)                    # clean text data
{ require("tm")
  x  =  gsub("<.*?>", " ", x)               # regex for removing HTML tags
  x  =  iconv(x, "latin1", "ASCII", sub="") # Keep only ASCII characters
  x  =  gsub("[^[:alnum:]]", " ", x)        # keep only alpha numeric 
  x  =  tolower(x)                          # convert to lower case characters
  x  =  removeNumbers(x)                    # removing numbers
  x  =  stripWhitespace(x)                  # removing white space
  x  =  gsub("^\\s+|\\s+$", "", x)          # remove leading and trailing white space
  return(x)
}

Create DTM

tok_fun = word_tokenizer
it_m = itoken(x,
              tokenizer = tok_fun,
              ids = data$id,
              progressbar = T)

vocab = create_vocabulary(it_m)
                                
pruned_vocab = prune_vocabulary(vocab,term_count_min = 1)

vectorizer = vocab_vectorizer(pruned_vocab)

dtm_m  = create_dtm(it_m, vectorizer)

dtm = as.DocumentTermMatrix(dtm_m, weighting = weightTf)
  a0 = (apply(dtm, 1, sum) > 0)   # build vector to identify non-empty docs
  dtm = dtm[a0,]                  # drop empty docs

Adjacency matrix to plot COG graph

senti.dtm = cbind(pos.tdm, neg.tdm) # COG for sentiment-laden words
senti.adj.mat = as.matrix(t(senti.dtm)) %*% as.matrix(senti.dtm)
diag(senti.adj.mat) = 0

Distilled COG function

  distill.cog = function(mat1, # input TCM ADJ MAT
                         title, # title for the graph
                         s,    # no. of central nodes
                         k1){  # max no. of connections  
    library(igraph)
    a = colSums(mat1) # collect colsums into a vector obj a
    b = order(-a)     # syntax for ordering vector in decr order  
    
    mat2 = mat1[b, b]     # order both rows and columns along vector b
    
    diag(mat2) =  0
    
    #go row by row and find top k adjacencies
    
    wc = NULL
    
    for (i1 in 1:s){ 
      thresh1 = mat2[i1,][order(-mat2[i1, ])[k1]]
      mat2[i1, mat2[i1,] < thresh1] = 0 
      mat2[i1, mat2[i1,] > 0 ] = 1
      word = names(mat2[i1, mat2[i1,] > 0])
      mat2[(i1+1):nrow(mat2), match(word,colnames(mat2))] = 0
      wc = c(wc,word)
    } # i1 loop ends
    
    
    mat3 = mat2[match(wc, colnames(mat2)), match(wc, colnames(mat2))]
    ord = colnames(mat2)[which(!is.na(match(colnames(mat2), colnames(mat3))))]  # removed any NAs from     the list
    mat4 = mat3[match(ord, colnames(mat3)), match(ord, colnames(mat3))]
    graph <- graph.adjacency(mat4, mode = "undirected", weighted=T)    # Create network object
    graph = simplify(graph) 
    V(graph)$color[1:s] = "green"
    V(graph)$color[(s+1):length(V(graph))] = "pink"
    
    graph = delete.vertices(graph, V(graph)[ degree(graph) == 0 ]) # delete singletons
    
    plot(graph, 
         layout = layout.kamada.kawai, 
         main = title)
    
  } # func ends

distill.cog(senti.adj.mat,   # adj mat obj 
            'Distilled COG of senti words (tf) - I',# plot title
            5,       # max #central nodes
            5)        # max #connections

Recommendations for making a Sequel

1. Frequently appearing positive words - The users have used the words like amazing, excellent,good,great and masterpiece in their reviews pointing that they liked the movie very much. All positive reviews have been rated with rating 10/10. Words like powerful and remarkable tell us that movie has a very powerful message which gets to the viewer very clearly and the user really likes that giving a rating of 10/10. Words like fine, nice and pretty have appeared in the reviews reflecting the beauty of the movie .

2. The sentiment for the movie mostly appears to be negative below the zero line. This means that are several negative aspects which should be avoided when making a sequel. Frequently used negative words - atrocities, evil, ghetto,horibble and worse reflect negative sentiments of the users. Words such as awful, overrated, poor and propaganda reflect negative sentiments.

3. We analyze the most positive review - The user likes saving of the Jew people and remembrance of the holocaust day. The user likes the star cast - Liam Neeson and Ben Kingsley. The user feels the incidents shown in the movie are true. The user likes different colors used in the movie.

4. We analyze the most negative review - The user thinks that the movie is flawed and biased towards Germans and is impossible to watch. The movie has deliberate immorality, obscenity, perversions and pornograhic dimensions.

5. Overall

Attributes/Aspects to be retained - Powerful message, Star cast - Liam Neeson and Ben Kingsley, True incidents, Different colors.

Attributes/Aspects to be changed - Dont show or reduce evil, horrible, immoral, obscene and pornographic incidents. The incidents shown should not reflect biasness towards a community or a group of people and create a propaganda about it.
